<link href="//api.tiles.mapbox.com/mapbox.js/v1.2.0/mapbox.css" rel="stylesheet" /><!--[if lte IE 8]><link href="//api.tiles.mapbox.com/mapbox.js/v1.2.0/mapbox.ie.css" rel="stylesheet" /><![endif]--><!--[if lt IE 9]><link href="/ie-lt-8.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" /><script src="//html5shim.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/html5.js"></script><![endif]--></head><body><div id="root"><nav id="nav"><ul><li class="home"><a href="/"><h1>Stone's Throw Urban Farm</h1></a></li><li class="about"><a class="about" href="/"><h2>about</h2></a><nav class="subnav"><ul><li><a class="farmers" href="/farmers"><h2>the farmers</h2></a></li><li><a class="farm" href="/farm"><h2>how we farm</h2></a></li><li><a class="find" href="/find-us"><h2>find us</h2></a></li><li><a class="contact" href="/contact"><h2>contact us</h2></a></li><li><a class="faq" href="/faq"><h2>FAQ</h2></a></li></ul></nav></li><li class="csa"><a href="/csa"><h2>join our CSA</h2></a><nav class="subnav"><ul><li><a href="/why-csa"><h2>why csa?</h2></a></li></ul></nav></li><li><a class="blog" href="//stonesthrowurbanfarm.wordpress.com/"><h2>blog</h2></a></li><li><a class="involved" href="/get-involved"><h2>get involved</h2></a></li></ul><div class="secondary"><a class="faq" href="/faq"><h2>FAQ</h2></a><a class="signup" href="/signup"><h2>Signup</h2></a></div></nav><section id="farming"><article><h2>How we Farm</h2><p>We grow our veggies using organic practices, with a mind toward ecological stewardship.</p><p>Although we aren’t certified organic (<a href="/faq">see our FAQ page for more information</a>), we never use any chemical or artificial fertilizers on our land and crops. We feed our plants and soil with lots of compost, and use organic turkey manure as well as compost tea for more concentrated fertilization. For pest control, we use floating row cover as a physical barrier, our two hands, and keen observation to keep pest levels below and acceptable threshold.</p>
<p>We do use fossil fuels on our farm, but always with a mind toward how to use less. We own and use a full size truck, but also own a cargo bike trailer, which we use for commuting between farm sites when possible. We till our land with a BCS walk-behind tractor, and do the majority of our cultivation with hoes and hands.</p><img alt="Pedal powered barrel composter" class="tall" src="/img/content/HWF1.jpg" /><h2>Farming as a Political Act</h2><p>We all love to farm - the chance to be outside, to work hand in hand with life and death, the bone-tired satisfaction at the end of a long day. We also love living in the city- the bustle and hum of life around us, the diversity of folks we interact with every day, the proximity of opportunity.</p><p>We see the abundance of vacant land in our neighborhoods. We notice that many of the folks, especially young folks, who live nearby are attracted to dangerous and harmful endeavors for lack of more productive, fulfilling things to do.</p><p>We think it makes sense to grow our most perishable, vitamin-rich foods close to where we live. It also makes sense to use those vacant lots for something productive. Growing food is also a great way to educate anyone who’s walking by and wants to learn. We like to educate our neighbors about how food is grown, to reconnect people with their food.</p><p>For us, farming is a political act. We have a vision for a more self-reliant economy in which we rely on the power of community and our own two hands, rather than entrusting our livelihood to complicated, profit-driven corporations. Every day, we wake up and work toward a society that is less sick and more well, less subdued and more empowered, capable, awake, and alive. Little steps, every day.</p><img alt="Three of the farmers standing behind the bike trailer stacked with produce" class="wide" src="/img/content/HWF2.jpg" /></article><aside><bq class="testimonial">We’re passionate about growing food for our community. We revel in making our living doing the hard, honest, sweaty, joyful work of farming.</bq><cite>Emily Hanson, Stone’s Throw farmer</cite></aside></section><div id="root_footer"></div><nav id="footer"><ul><li><p>(612) 454-0585</p><p><a href="mailto:stonesthrowurbanfarm@gmail.com">Contact Us</a></p></li><li><p>2216 Elliot Avenue S</p><p>Minneapolis, MN 55404</p></li><li><p>© 2013 Stone's Urban Farm.</p><p>All rights reserved.</p></li><li><p>Site by Asa Diebolt, Kjell O.</p><p>Typed in: <a href="//www.exljbris.com/delicious.html">Delicious</a> and Arial </p></li></ul></nav></div><script src="//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.8/jquery.min.js"></script><script src="//api.tiles.mapbox.com/mapbox.js/v1.2.0/mapbox.js"></script></body></html>